<section class="article-container" data-stats-ve="35"><h2 class="guide-title">US states privacy laws guidance</h2><h1>Supporting the IAB's Global Privacy Platform</h1><div class="article-content-container"><div class="drop-head">Helping publishers comply with U.S. privacy laws through a standardized framework</div><div class="guide-button-container" data-stats-ve="46"><a class="guide-button" aria-label="Previous: Restricted data processing settings in Google’s publisher ad tags" data-stats-action="7" href="/admanager/answer/9598414?hl=en&ref_topic=10383232"><svg viewbox="0 0 48 48"><path d="M30.83 32.67l-9.17-9.17 9.17-9.17L28 11.5l-12 12 12 12z"></path></svg></a><a class="guide-button next" aria-label="Next: Integration with IAB CCPA Framework Technical Specifications" data-stats-action="6" href="/admanager/answer/9603027?hl=en&ref_topic=10383232"><span>Next: Integration with IAB CCPA Framework Technical Specifications</span><svg viewbox="0 0 48 48"><path d="M17.17 32.92l9.17-9.17-9.17-9.17L20 11.75l12 12-12 12z"></path></svg></a></div><div class="cc"><p>Developed by the IAB’s Tech Lab, the <a href="https://iabtechlab.com/gpp/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Global Privacy Platform (GPP)</a> is a standardized framework for storing and passing user privacy consent preferences. </p>

<p>By Q4 2023, Ad Manager will support the GPP for publishers and consent management platforms (CMPs) that wish to use the framework for compliance with US privacy laws. The use of GPP or a consent management platform is not a requirement for US states with applicable privacy laws.</p>

<p>For ads served to users in the European Economic Area or the UK, Ad Manager will continue to use the IAB Europe TCF through the use of a <a href="https://support.google.com/admanager/answer/13554116" rel="noopener">certified Consent Management Platform</a>. TCF strings sent through the GPP will not be accepted.</p>

<p>While the IAB intends to deprecate the US Privacy String by end of January 2024, in favor of GPP, Ad Manager will continue to read the US Privacy String in order to support apps partners. The US Privacy String may be deprecated in future SDK releases. Once fully supported by Ad Manager, it is recommended that publishers and CMPs move forward with GPP strings, instead of the US Privacy String, if they choose to use an IAB framework for US state privacy law compliance.</p>

<h2>Global Privacy Platform specifications</h2>

<p>Ad Manager will only accept the following US States strings within GPP: <a href="https://github.com/InteractiveAdvertisingBureau/Global-Privacy-Platform/blob/main/Sections/US-States/CA/GPP%20Extension%3A%20IAB%20Privacy%E2%80%99s%20California%20Privacy%20Technical%20Specification.md">California</a>, <a href="https://github.com/InteractiveAdvertisingBureau/Global-Privacy-Platform/blob/main/Sections/US-States/VA/GPP%20Extension%3A%20IAB%20Privacy%E2%80%99s%20Virginia%20Privacy%20Technical%20Specification.md">Virginia</a>, <a href="https://github.com/InteractiveAdvertisingBureau/Global-Privacy-Platform/blob/main/Sections/US-States/CO/GPP%20Extension%3A%20IAB%20Privacy%E2%80%99s%20Colorado%20Privacy%20Technical%20Specification.md">Colorado</a>, <a href="https://github.com/InteractiveAdvertisingBureau/Global-Privacy-Platform/blob/main/Sections/US-States/CT/GPP%20Extension%3A%20IAB%20Privacy%E2%80%99s%20Connecticut%20Privacy%20Technical%20Specification.md">Connecticut</a>. </p>

<p>Ad Manager will not accept US National, IAB Canada TCF, US Privacy String, US States Utah, or IAB EU TCF v2.2 as part of GPP support. </p>

<p>Publishers should work with their CMP partners to ensure that TC strings are generated based on the <a href="https://iabeurope.eu/tcf-2-0/">IAB TCF v2.0 spec</a>.</p>

<div><h3>California</h3>

<p>Google will trigger restricted data processing (RDP) if any the following criteria are met:</p>

<ul>
  <li>User opted out of <em>Sale of the Consumer's Personal Information</em>.</li>
  <li>User opted out of <em>Sharing of the Consumer's Personal Information</em>.</li>
</ul>

<p>Google only reads the above fields of the US States string for California.</p>

<h3>Virginia, Connecticut, Colorado</h3>

<p>Google will trigger restricted data processing (RDP) if any the following criteria are met:</p>

<ul>
  <li>User opted out of <em>Sale of the Consumer's Personal Information</em>.</li>
  <li>User opted out of <em>Processing the Consumer's Personal Data for Targeted Advertising.</em></li>
</ul>

<p>Google only reads the above fields of the US States string for Virginia, Connecticut, Colorado.</p>

<h2>Consent signals for Minors using the Global Privacy Platform</h2>

<p>The IAB’s Global Privacy Platform offers the ability for you, or your CMP, to pass relevant consent signals in response to US state privacy laws requiring additional considerations for minor and/or child-directed inventory. We recommend that publishers continue to use our tools for tagging sites, apps, and requests for child directed treatment to facilitate compliance with COPPA and other relevant regulations (<a href="https://support.google.com/adsense/answer/3248194" rel="noopener" target="_blank">AdSense</a>, <a href="https://support.google.com/admob/answer/6219315" rel="noopener" target="_blank">AdMob</a>, and <a href="https://support.google.com/admanager/answer/3671211" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Ad Manager</a>).</p>

<h3>California</h3>

<p>Requests will be marked for child-directed treatment (TFCD) if any of the following criteria are met:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Consent or no consent to <em>Sell the Personal Information of Consumers Less Than 16 years of Age</em></li>
  <li>Consent or no consent to <em>Share the Personal Information of Consumers Less Than 16 years of Age</em></li>
</ul>

<h3>Virginia, Colorado</h3>

<p>Requests will be marked for child-directed treatment (TFCD) if the following criteria are met:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Consent or no consent to <em>Process Sensitive Data from a Known Child</em></li>
</ul>

<h3>Connecticut</h3>

<p>Requests will be marked for child-directed treatment (TFCD) if any of the following criteria are met:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Consent or no consent to <em>Consent to Process Sensitive Data from a Known Child</em></li>
  <li>Requests will trigger restricted data processing (RDP) if any the following criteria are met:</li>
  <li>No consent to <em>Sell the Personal Data of Consumers At Least 13 Years of Age but Younger Than 16 Years of Age</em></li>
  <li>No consent to<em> Process the Personal Data of Consumers At Least 13 Years of Age but Younger Than 16 Years of Age for Purposes of Targeted Advertising.</em></li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="note">
  <div class="no-margin"><strong>Note</strong>: The Global Privacy Platform is one of multiple methods that publishers can use to support their compliance with <a href="/admanager/answer/9561023" rel="noopener">US state privacy laws</a>.</div>
</div>

readabilityObject.title: Supporting the IAB's Global Privacy Platform
readabilityObject.content:
US states privacy laws guidance

Helping publishers comply with U.S. privacy laws through a standardized framework

Next: Integration with IAB CCPA Framework Technical Specifications

Developed by the IAB’s Tech Lab, the Global Privacy Platform (GPP) is a standardized framework for storing and passing user privacy consent preferences. 

By Q4 2023, Ad Manager will support the GPP for publishers and consent management platforms (CMPs) that wish to use the framework for compliance with US privacy laws. The use of GPP or a consent management platform is not a requirement for US states with applicable privacy laws.

For ads served to users in the European Economic Area or the UK, Ad Manager will continue to use the IAB Europe TCF through the use of a certified Consent Management Platform. TCF strings sent through the GPP will not be accepted.

While the IAB intends to deprecate the US Privacy String by end of January 2024, in favor of GPP, Ad Manager will continue to read the US Privacy String in order to support apps partners. The US Privacy String may be deprecated in future SDK releases. Once fully supported by Ad Manager, it is recommended that publishers and CMPs move forward with GPP strings, instead of the US Privacy String, if they choose to use an IAB framework for US state privacy law compliance.

Global Privacy Platform specifications

Ad Manager will only accept the following US States strings within GPP: California, Virginia, Colorado, Connecticut. 

Ad Manager will not accept US National, IAB Canada TCF, US Privacy String, US States Utah, or IAB EU TCF v2.2 as part of GPP support. 

Publishers should work with their CMP partners to ensure that TC strings are generated based on the IAB TCF v2.0 spec.

California

Google will trigger restricted data processing (RDP) if any the following criteria are met:

  • User opted out of Sale of the Consumer's Personal Information.
  • User opted out of Sharing of the Consumer's Personal Information.

Google only reads the above fields of the US States string for California.

Virginia, Connecticut, Colorado

Google will trigger restricted data processing (RDP) if any the following criteria are met:

  • User opted out of Sale of the Consumer's Personal Information.
  • User opted out of Processing the Consumer's Personal Data for Targeted Advertising.

Google only reads the above fields of the US States string for Virginia, Connecticut, Colorado.

Consent signals for Minors using the Global Privacy Platform

The IAB’s Global Privacy Platform offers the ability for you, or your CMP, to pass relevant consent signals in response to US state privacy laws requiring additional considerations for minor and/or child-directed inventory. We recommend that publishers continue to use our tools for tagging sites, apps, and requests for child directed treatment to facilitate compliance with COPPA and other relevant regulations (AdSense, AdMob, and Ad Manager).

California

Requests will be marked for child-directed treatment (TFCD) if any of the following criteria are met:

  • Consent or no consent to Sell the Personal Information of Consumers Less Than 16 years of Age
  • Consent or no consent to Share the Personal Information of Consumers Less Than 16 years of Age

Virginia, Colorado

Requests will be marked for child-directed treatment (TFCD) if the following criteria are met:

  • Consent or no consent to Process Sensitive Data from a Known Child

Connecticut

Requests will be marked for child-directed treatment (TFCD) if any of the following criteria are met:

  • Consent or no consent to Consent to Process Sensitive Data from a Known Child
  • Requests will trigger restricted data processing (RDP) if any the following criteria are met:
  • No consent to Sell the Personal Data of Consumers At Least 13 Years of Age but Younger Than 16 Years of Age
  • No consent to Process the Personal Data of Consumers At Least 13 Years of Age but Younger Than 16 Years of Age for Purposes of Targeted Advertising.

Note: The Global Privacy Platform is one of multiple methods that publishers can use to support their compliance with US state privacy laws.

Next: Integration with IAB CCPA Framework Technical Specifications

Was this helpful?

How can we improve it?
